          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Canadian PM announces elections</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: With just nine days after his appointment, PM Mark Carney called for snap elections on April 28.</strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Canada heads to the polls on April 28 after newly appointed PM Mark Carney <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-03-2025-h3-3-called-a-snap-election" target="_blank">called a snap election</a> nine days into his term. The ongoing trade war with the US dominates the election. President Trump‚Äôs stringent tariffs and calls for Canada to become America‚Äôs 51st state have prioritized this. Carney will go head-to-head with Conservative leader Pierre Poilievre, whose party has been leading in national polls since mid-2023. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">The other key issues dominating the campaign are the cost of living and economic security. Carney, a former central banker, is seeking a mandate to defend Canadian sovereignty; he warns that Trump wants to take Canada. Conservative leader Pierre Poilievre accuses Carney and the Liberals of economic mismanagement. He says the past decade was a "lost Liberal decade." </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Carney ditched Trudeau‚Äôs carbon tax and pledged further retaliation against US tariffs. However, he faces criticism for his inexperience, as he has no previous political position. The more left-leaning New Democratic Party (NDP) and Quebec's nationalists compete for influence. The NDP accuses the two major parties of favoring the wealthy. Polls suggest a tight race as Canadians prepare for a high-stakes, five-week campaign.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
