          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Is Quebec sovereignty still an issue?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/flag-of-quebec.png" alt="Flag of Quebec" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Flag of Quebec. Credits: The Loop</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Quebec sovereignty remains an ongoing political issue, but it is not as severe as it once was. The movement was at its highest in the 1980s and 1990s, with significant referendums in 1980 and 1995. The 1995 referendum was quite close, with the ‚ÄúNo‚Äù side winning by less than one percent. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-03-2025-f1-6-parti-quebecois" target="_blank">Parti Qu√©b√©cois</a>, the main pro-sovereignty party, still exists and has recently gained some support, but overall, polls show fewer Quebecers now want independence.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Many younger people feel less connected to the idea of separating from Canada. They care more about protecting French language rights and promoting Quebec‚Äôs distinct identity within Canada than sovereignty. However, the ‚ÄúYes‚Äù vote support has remained stable at around 35 percent for the last few years. While the people believe their traditions can be preserved in independent Quebec, they fear the economic and environmental consequences. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          While the issue isn‚Äôt as urgent as it once was, it hasn‚Äôt disappeared. The Parti Qu√©b√©cois is still popular and influential. The problem still surfaces in politics, especially during elections or when debates about language laws and federal-provincial relations arise. The Parti Qu√©b√©cois even led the polls recently in Quebec, but not by a margin that is considerable enough to where separatism is on the table.</p>
         
          
